Si este libro se perdiere como suele  suceder suplico qel quelo nulle ma lo sepa volvere. Con dos cuartos en la mano y sino dos puntu pies y sino sabe mi nombre a quis buyo lo pondre [?].

comment.author: 92363641@N06
comment.text:
"Si este libro se perdiere como suele suceder suplico qel quelo halle me lo sepa bolber.
Con dos cuartos en la mano y sino dos puntapies y sino sabe mi nombre aqui bajo lo pondre: Soy de Ysydro Martinez."

In current Spanish, would be:
Si este libro se perdiere como suele suceder, 
suplico al que lo halle que lo sepa devolver.
Con dos cuartos en la mano, y si no, dos puntapiés.
Y si no sabe mi nombre, aquí abajo lo pondré:
Soy de Isidro Martínez.

The meaning of the second part would be that the owner will give 2 cuartos to he who finds the lost book,  but, as 'cuarto' is a coin of low value, if he complains , then the award will be 2 kicks.

Autograph of Samuel W. Fernberger in red pencil and stamp the S.W. Fernberger Collection of Psychology of the University of Pennsylvania Libraries [Samuel Weiller Fernberger (1887-1956) received his Ph.D. in psychology from the University of Pennsylvania in 1912 and was a member of the faculty at Clark University from 1912 until his death. F. W. Irwin wrote in Fernberger's obituary in The American Journal of Psychology, Vol. 69.4 (1956), p. 677-678:
At all stages of his career he exhibited an interest in those applications of experimental psychology that employed rigorous, preferably psychophysical, methods. He once testified before the Public Service Commission of Pennsylvania as an expert for the complainant in an action brought by the Yellow Cab Company of Philadelphia to prevent the use by others of taxicabs with colors alleged to resemble too closely the color of Yellow Cabs. His testimony involved not only verbal opinions but also the performance of demonstrations in the hearing room in the presence of the examiner and the interested parties. He mixed colors on a rotary color mixer to match the colors of the complainant's and respondent's cabs, showed that they were closely similar -- they differed by not more than three just noticeable differences along the base of a model of the color solid that was also produced -- and that their resemblance increased as the illumination of the room was decreased.
Shortly before his death Fernberger donated a collection of psychological books and journals to the University of Pennsylvania as the Samuel W. Fernberger Collection of Psychology. Established form: Fernberger, Samuel Weiller, ǂd 1887-1956].

(Penn's copy is number 18 of a limited edition of 400, of which 30 were printed on hand-made paper, bound in leather and signed by the author.) Michel received the Georg-Büchner-Preis in 1925. From 1906 to 1930 he contributed regularly to the leftist magazine Die Weltbühne, edited by Nobel Peace Prize winner Carl von Ossietzky, with whom Michel clashed in 1933 over the staging of Bertolt Brecht's Saint Joan of the Stockyards (which Michel characterized as "an artistically disguised attempt to kill our soul"). Established form: Michel, Wilhelm, ‡d 1877-1942.

and printed books. The 'Vorbericht' explains
that Fallersleben having been deprived of his
Professorship at Breslau for publishing his

part with his library which he had gathered
with such love and enthusiasm over a period
of 30 years. Some of his books had already
found their way to the auction room in
May 1843. The remainder, here cataloged,
which comprised the larger and more
valuable portion of his library having
failed to find a buyer among the 'public'
libraries of his own country he now
offered to 'all the world' for 2000 Thalers.

Here is the complete story...my father, Celestino Joaristi (1915-     ) attended UPenn in the late 1930's....he never graduated from Wharton because my grandfather died his junior year and he had to go back to Cuba  to take over the family business.  In his haste to get back Cuba he probably left the book in the dorm.  In any case I am glad that you guys have it and I am sure that would have been his wish.  He is now 97 and, sadly, senile.  His biggest regret was not graduating from UPenn, but there was no one left to manage my grandfathers business.  At a very young age (early 20's) he successfully turned the family hardware business into the "Home Depot" of Cuba.  All this effort only to see Fidel Castro nationalize my fathers company in 1960.  I hope this information is of value to you.
Best
Pedro Celestino Joaristi

comment.author: 58558794@N07
comment.text:
Thank you so much for providing this wonderful information about your father and grandfather.  I just went to check our accession books to find out when and where we got the book.  It turns out that we purchased it in 1951 from Allen's Book Store in Philadelphia, so the book must have traveled around a bit between the time your father left Penn and its arrival on our shelves.  I do hope that your daughter will get a chance to come see it in person!

One of the joys of working with rare books is learning about their histories--who owned them, how far did they travel from the press where they were printed, and how did they reach our collection?  Too often, we only have a very incomplete picture so it is always very special when we are able to connect the books with real living people.  Thank you for doing this for us!

Best wishes,
Regan

comment.author: 70213421@N02
comment.text: Inscription: James Moon's I believe this James Moon could be the grandson of a Quaker Englishman from Bristol named James Moon who immigrated to Bucks County, PA. with his wife Joan and their six children in 1682. The family is said to perhaps have sailed with William Penn on the "Welcome" and landed in New Castle, DE. Cf. worldconnect.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/igm.... The family then settled in Fallsington, in Falls Township, Bucks County, near Morrisville, and eventually purchased a 125 acre farm that is still in the family today (now called Snipes Farm). The family was actively involved with the Falls Monthly Meeting. There are two headings for James Moon of Bucks County in VIAF, and I believe the correct one is Moon, James, but there are no dates so it is difficult to tell. The James Moon who inscribed these pamphlets may be the grandson of James Moon Sr., and he remained in Bucks County and began to grow and sell ornamental trees in 1767, beginning a tradition of horticulture in the family. He was born in 1713 and is the eldest son of Roger Moon (James Moon Sr.'s youngest child) and Ann Nutt Moon. He died in 1796. Cf. pagenweb.org/~bucks/BIOS_DAVIS/moonfamily.html The autographs of James Moon look like a match to this one found here. This document (and there are several others for sale by this auction house) is a Quaker slave manumission from Bucks County, PA. in 1777. It is a Quaker document declaring a particular slave to be freed on a particular date in the future, and James Moon has signed these documents as a witness.
